Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Roughly chop @peanuts{1/2%ounce}. Dice @sweet potatoes{1} into 1⁄2-inch pieces. 
Trim @green beans{6%ounce} if necessary and cut into 11⁄2-inch pieces. Quarter 
@lime{1}. Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}.

Once water is boiling, add @lo mein noodles{4.5%ounce} to pot. Cook, stirring 
occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Drain noodles and rinse under cold water for ~{30%seconds}.

While noodles are cooking, heat a large, dry pan over medium-high heat. Add 
peanuts and cook, stirring frequently, until golden brown and fragrant, 
~{2-3%minutes}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a plate.

Rinse @shrimp{10%ounce} under cold water and pat dry with #paper towels{} or 
open package of chicken and drain off any excess liquid. Heat a drizzle of 
@cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a separate large pan over medium-high heat. Add 
shrimp or chicken in a single layer; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, 
stirring occasionally, until cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for peanuts over medium-high heat. Add sweet 
potato and a pinch of salt. Cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and 
slightly tender, ~{7%minutes}. (Lower heat if sweet potato starts to brown too 
quickly.)

While sweet potato cooks, in a #medium bowl{}, whisk together @coconut milk{1}, 
@sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce}, @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, half the 
@curry powder{1%tablespoon}, and 1⁄2 cup water (all the curry powder and 1 cup 
water for 4 servings).

Stir green beans and sauce mixture into pan with sweet potato. Bring to a boil, 
then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until veggies are tender, 
~{6-8%minutes}.

> If sauce seems too thick, add a splash of water.

Remove from heat.

Add drained noodles and juice from half the lime to pan with veggies and sauce; 
toss to coat. Season with salt.

Add shrimp or chicken to pan along with drained noodles and lime juice.

Divide coconut curry noodles between #bowls{} and top with peanuts and cilantro. 
Squeeze remaining lime wedges over the top and serve.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.